<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="428" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1855,2026]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1437,151,321]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="428" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,456,1855,1881]" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">Diagnosis &amp; remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Fitzgerald, 2021" authorityName="Fitzgerald" authorityYear="2021" box="[471,649,1855,1881]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leptomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juxtafurcatus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[471,649,1855,1881]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">L. juxtafurcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[658,723,1855,1881]" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[658,723,1855,1881]" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be distinguished from all New World congeners except 
<taxonomicName authority="Borkent" authorityName="Borkent" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leptomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furcatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">L. furcatus</emphasis>
Borkent
</taxonomicName>
by sternite nine with a pair of subapical pointed lobes and gonocoxites extending posteriorly as a pair of forcipate lobes. 
<taxonomicName authority="Fitzgerald, 2021" authorityName="Fitzgerald" authorityYear="2021" box="[414,592,1927,1953]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leptomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juxtafurcatus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[414,592,1927,1953]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">L. juxtafurcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[599,663,1927,1953]" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[599,663,1927,1953]" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[874,995,1927,1953]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leptomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furcatus">
<emphasis box="[874,995,1927,1953]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">L. furcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and will key to this species in 
<bibRefCitation author="Borkent, C. J. &amp; Wheeler, T. A." pageId="4" pageNumber="427" pagination="1 - 117" refId="ref4224" refString="Borkent, C. J. &amp; Wheeler, T. A. (2012) Systematics and Phylogeny of Leptomorphus Curtis (Diptera: Mycetophilidae). Zootaxa, 3549 (1), 1 - 117. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3549.1.1" type="journal article" year="2012">Borkent and Wheeler (2012)</bibRefCitation>
, but can be distinguished by the shape of the gonocoxites which are simple (with basal and distal portions continuous), forcipate, tapering apically, and apically unforked, whereas the gonocoxite of 
<taxonomicName box="[1315,1436,1999,2025]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leptomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furcatus">
<emphasis box="[1315,1436,1999,2025]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">L. furcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is of much different form; the dorsal edge of the gonocoxite is longitudinally cleft, setting off the basal and distal portions of the gonocoxite and forming a strong keel-like shoulder at the apex of the basal portion (not apparent in 
<bibRefCitation author="Borkent, C. J. &amp; Wheeler, T. A." box="[151,434,223,249]" pageId="5" pageNumber="428" pagination="1 - 117" refId="ref4224" refString="Borkent, C. J. &amp; Wheeler, T. A. (2012) Systematics and Phylogeny of Leptomorphus Curtis (Diptera: Mycetophilidae). Zootaxa, 3549 (1), 1 - 117. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3549.1.1" type="journal article" year="2012">Borkent &amp; Wheeler 2012</bibRefCitation>
, Fig. 104). Additionally, the more distal portion of the gonocoxite of 
<taxonomicName box="[1195,1315,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Mycetophilidae" genus="Leptomorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="428" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furcatus">
<emphasis box="[1195,1315,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="428">L. furcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is broader, with the medial edge more expanded and blade-like, asetose and the apex of the gonocoxite slightly forked (
<bibRefCitation author="Borkent, C. J. &amp; Wheeler, T. A." pageId="5" pageNumber="428" pagination="1 - 117" refId="ref4224" refString="Borkent, C. J. &amp; Wheeler, T. A. (2012) Systematics and Phylogeny of Leptomorphus Curtis (Diptera: Mycetophilidae). Zootaxa, 3549 (1), 1 - 117. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3549.1.1" type="journal article" year="2012">Borkent &amp; Wheeler 2012</bibRefCitation>
, Fig. 104).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
